{"id":"2111.07781","submitter":"Achal Mahajan","authors":"Achal Mahajan and David Saintillan","title":"Self-induced hydrodynamic coil-stretch transition of active polymers","comments":"11 pages, 8 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.105.014608","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft physics.bio-ph physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We analyze the conformational dynamics and statistical properties of an\nactive polymer model. The polymer is described as a freely-jointed bead-rod\nchain subject to stochastic active force dipoles that act on the suspending\nsolvent where they drive long-ranged fluid flows. Using Langevin simulations of\nisolated chains in unconfined domains, we show how the coupling of active flows\nwith polymer conformations leads to emergent dynamics. Systems with contractile\ndipoles behave similarly to passive Brownian chains with enhanced fluctuations\ndue to dipolar flows. In systems with extensile dipoles, however, our\nsimulations uncover an active coil-stretch transition whereby the polymer\nspontaneously unfolds and stretches out in its own self-induced hydrodynamic\nflow, and we characterize this transition in terms of a dimensionless activity\nparameter comparing active dipolar forces to thermal fluctuations. We discuss\nour findings in the context of the classic coil-stretch transition of passive\npolymers in extensional flows, and complement our simulations with a simple\nkinetic model for an active trimer.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Nov 2021 01:02:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 12 Jan 2022 13:51:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-09"}
